WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.680
Digital border walls and facial recognition aren't just American issues, they're already

00:00:05.680 --> 00:00:07.840
active across Canada.

00:00:07.840 --> 00:00:12.800
Police are using big data to shift from reacting to crimes to predicting them.

00:00:12.800 --> 00:00:16.960
But this triggers a fatal flaw, algorithmic bias.

00:00:16.960 --> 00:00:22.280
Take the Saskatchewan Police Predictive Analytics Lab, which is developing algorithms to forecast

00:00:22.280 --> 00:00:23.880
repeat offenders.

00:00:23.880 --> 00:00:28.760
To learn what a high-risk offender looks like, the algorithm trains on massive datasets

00:00:28.760 --> 00:00:31.480
of historical Canadian arrest records.

00:00:31.480 --> 00:00:36.600
But independent legal reviews reveal this data isn't a neutral map of crime, it's a map

00:00:36.600 --> 00:00:42.440
of past police behavior, skewed by a legacy of systemic racism and over-policing.

00:00:42.440 --> 00:00:47.400
Lacking social context, the algorithm blindly accepts these records as ground truth.

00:00:47.400 --> 00:00:52.320
It mathematically links marginalized identities to higher crime rates, outputting a high-risk

00:00:52.320 --> 00:00:53.320
score.

00:00:53.320 --> 00:00:57.720
Officers are deployed based on these objective scores, leading to new arrests in those exact

00:00:57.720 --> 00:00:59.320
same communities.

00:00:59.320 --> 00:01:03.840
These new arrests feed directly back into the database, confirming the prediction and creating

00:01:03.840 --> 00:01:06.160
a self-fulfilling feedback loop.

00:01:06.160 --> 00:01:10.320
Experts warn this mechanism likely violates the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms,

00:01:10.320 --> 00:01:14.000
disguising adverse impact discrimination as neutral science.

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:16.960
So what about that Saskatchewan Risk Forecasting Lab?

00:01:16.960 --> 00:01:21.400
Unless it rejects this flawed historical data, it won't predict a new future.

00:01:21.400 --> 00:01:23.480
It will just mathematically enforce the past.
